This is a cool test, but tournaments are pretty terrible for getting good data. Tournaments are only useful for comparing extremely large numbers where each permutation can't be checked. But tournament ranking assumes that the transitive property applies, and that is so incredibly unlikely to be true for just some metric that is based in physical reality. It's not even true for sets of numbers greater than size one.

The data of the "overall winner" is completely useless. The data of which thread one against which other thread is quite useful and interesting. I like this study, its gives useful data that other wheedwhacker comparisons dont get to, but i think the way you modeled your comparisons pretty much ruins the conclusion. Tournament style is bad for making good conclusions

As you mentioned, Absolutely unscientific and no truly presenting their true value.
A more thorough experiment is needed in order to know their true value.
Weedeater line types could behave totally different, when tested on weed and other natural plants.
The test itself should also be repeated several times under the same conditions for each weedeater, then again changing conditions and also repeated several times.
Only when there are enough tests performed, one can claim that statistically this or that performs its job better.
The tests should also include other factors apart from fracture, such as and speed and easiness of cut with each contact, the influence of shape on the quantity, quality and diameter of cut weed. It might be that certain types perform better for a certain diameter, while others perform better for a different diameter.
The same deviation might apply for different types of weed.

Since there are many factors that weren't taken into consideration, when should really consider this experiment as funny, but in no way proving anything.

The real question is how does RPM effect this when you can clearly hear two engines running at different rpms. How would that change the outcome? If they are both identical rpms only off by 50rpm or less, what is going to actually win? Centrifugal force will cause any of them to be more sturdy then what they are. Shape is a factor, rpm is a factor, core density all being relevant.

Typically on trimmer line with a core the core is a softer material so that shell of the can be a harder material to help with wear while keeping flexibility, it also helps having a harder shell with the line getting hot in the eyelet of the head and welding together and then not wanting to feed. This is information being passed on from the manufacture of the lines (husqvarna and oregon) not my opinion. Also both manufacturers when I spoke with their reps (regional sales/tech support the upper level guys with direct factory connections not your sales floor guys) gave the same explanation of what they were wishing to accomplish through the dual material line.

It was the final show down, everything Sharp Squared worked his entire life for was right in front of him, with in his grasp. He looked across the ring, a blank emotionless face stared back; eyes filled with blood lust, this was the last hurdle, this was Razor Core.

As the fight begin both were evenly matched in speed and technique, Razor had the advantage in raw strength but Sharp did not back down. They traded blow for blow, strike after strike . Slowly Sharp was getting worn down by Razor's sheer raw power, if it kept going like this he wouldn't last much longer. In the second round, Sharp went on the offensive throwing caution to the wind and going in for the kill. But a momentary lapse of judgment gave Razor the perfect opportunity... a deadly strike on a vital point. Sharp went down... his entire body was in agony. Was this it, after everything he's been through, all his brothers and friends he cut through to get to this stage .... was this the end. He wobbled, a smile drew across Razors face. Like an experienced hunter he sensed that the end was near for his prey. There was a moment of silence. Razor charged, blow after blow, Sharp was using all of his strength just to keep everything together. HIs consciousness begin to fade. Was this the end... No.... no.. NEVER. He dove towards Razor, madness in his eyes, and with everything that was left in his feeble broken body Sharp screamed swinging his fists in desperation. The hunter has suddenly become the prey, Razor hesitated, but that split second was all the Sharp needed. BANG. The crowd went silent ... Razor's broken body lay across the canvas. He was dead.

Four omnipotent giants appeared from the shadows. "ARE YOU HAPPY NOW, IS THIS WHAT YOU WANTED!" Sharp roared as his limp body slumped to the ground. But he knew they did not speak his language, nor he theirs. They simply appeared one day and forced his people to slaughter each other for their entertainment. But it was over, finally it was all over.... Sharp's eyes began to close, he could rest now, he could finally rest... He has won.

First of all – AWESOME VIDEO – seriously, I watched to the end and loved it. You always make the coolest videos.
Now for me to get really nerdy. You have a couple problems with your design.
The first problem is you are assuming if one line breaks from another line then it would also be broken sooner from other lines. But the interaction of the lines when they hit each other is probably more like Rock-Paper-Scissors than like box car races.
Second problem is that you are using a surrogate measure. I’m assuming your ultimate question is; “Which line will whack the most weeds in a season and will need the least amount of replacement?” (unless, of course, your ultimate question is to see what video you can get the most views on… in which case you succeeded, and I would ask that you keep it up because I seriously love the videos).
If your goal is to find out which line works, the best then you would actually want to do a different study. This is analogous to the surrogate measures of blood pressure measurements with antihypertensives compared to the patient-oriented outcomes of myocardial infarction and stroke. Patients don’t really care what the blood pressure number is… they care if they are going to have a stroke or not.
Similarly, we don’t care if one line breaks the other, we care if we will need to buy and replace more weed whacker line or not.
So a better design might be using one line for a month and measuring how much you go through. Then another line for a month and measure how much you go through, etc.
And an even better design would be to get lawn care companies to use different weed whacker line over a period of time and blind them to what they’re using. Then measure how much they went through AND give them a questionnaire to fill out regarding ease of use and efficacy/efficiency of the line. At the end of the study, you can weigh the pros and cons of consumption of line vs efficiency of the cut and ease of use. Tough to do that study though…
And an even more interesting comparison would be which line works best on which weed whacker – some are faster than others, some give out more line than others, some have a different angle of attack (bend in the pole) than others… and some people are of different heights (making the angle different). I’d bet the average homeowner doing their own lawn care will use line at a different rate than the a lawn care company… but we would need another study for that.

Also I think the line on the spool has a huge factor. Whichever one becomes taunt first has a tendency to cross its plastic threshold, and causes the break. Like over hardened metal. While the one that typically gets tangled on has a bit of slack between line and spool, allowing a little bit of an edge to absorb some forces. Another thing, is the Facets of some of the lines, I think has a tendency to add failure points. If you ever do a 4th video, it'd be cool to make custom heads that you only clamp 5 inches of line to. No spools. Test a faceted group of line, then a cylindrical group. Battle the two winners there. Also you can do educational content, or BTS videos on why these facets matter, or dont etc.. and you can recall your plastic, elastic strength video from a little while back, and show how it all ties together into everyday thinking. Sorry this was a long response, but I enjoy the content, and I figured I'd offer a bit of free brainstorming. Thanks for what y'all do!

sharp^2 was cheated! that was clearly a mounting issue rather than an aspect of the strand itself.

seriously though: mounting issues are a huge aspect of the durability and performance of these things in practice since that has a huge effect on how tension functions and energy dissipates in the strand, hard mounts sound like a clear looser in that regard but going purely by experience auto-feeding heads on weed eaters burn through thread several times faster than a hard mount (to the point where they will eat a spool in about the time the hard mount needs to be changed 3 times, they ARE way more time effective though), I'd assume a squishy version of a hard mount would be the best overall but I've never actually seen that (erm, relatively squishy, I'm thinkin' something like a bicycle brake).
actually...huh, literally just adding a braking system to an autofeeding head would be a pretty solid best of both worlds solution: you can tell the condition of the thread from instant to instant by the sound so that is absolutely something you can implement operator-control on and expect it to work well with most operators.

My initial feeling, if the loss condition is breakage, is that the Razor Core will win, because at a glance at least said core seems like it would offer greater durability.


Edit: Well, I had the right idea, I just neglected to consider that the Sharp Square has the same advantage. I actually realized this during the first Sharp Square match and found myself thinking that I might have made a mistake.

I correctly identified what was probably the most important factor in success of both the winner and the runner-up, I just wasn't observant and made a rather quick prediction instead of pausing for a few minutes to really consider each option. Sharp Square being gray on gray while Razor Core has the orange and gray contrast making it much more visible at a glance, along with it having "core" right in the name, are probably why I immediately noticed it for the latter but overlooked it for the former. I should have taken a bit more time looking them all over, but I wanted to keep watching the video so I made a quick decision instead.

1:00 seeing the tournament chart, my first thought is "this is already a flawed test, isn't it?"

Since you like being smarter every day, I'll explain like that xkcd commandment decrees:
When you do a single-elimination tournament brackets like this, the winner is heavily dependent on the match-ups. It isn't as straight-cut (pun intended) as the winner actually being best, as any of those that lost without battling the winner, is likely better than the winner. In addition to that, if it is single-elimination you also have entries losing on poor luck, and in reality each matchup should have a statistically significant amount of fights.
Ideally, you should avoid brackets entirely, as each entry needs to fight all the other entries. This is however unfeasible in reality, as the time-complexity is approx O(n^2), which is why ie. chess tournaments uses a few fights, and a sort of scoring system as a heuristic instead. But it is also rather shoddy, a better way would be to find the winner from a regular tournament, then have it fight all other entries (because the only entry who really matters, is 1st-place). Any that it loses against, is then also required to recursively fight all other entries - making the worst-case time-complexity still the same, but likely to be lower in reality (especially when you remove or dont add entries that has no chance of becoming the winner despite winning over a winner-candidate, from/to the set of winner-candidates). This is because any top-ranker is likely a top-ranker for a reason, so the worthless entries should be failing their fights against any other top-ranker.

However, if worst-case is deemed important, then you could at least count degrees of separation (if A fought B, that is 0 degrees. If A hasn't fought C, and B fought C then A has 1 degree of separation to C. And so on), and force the winner (and those winning over winner) to fight entries which are n degrees separated.
If you care for more than merely identifying 1st-place, you will also want to have losers fight each-other in losers-brackets.

And this wall-of-text is why tournament arcs in anime are bad! :D

I would wager it's partly because rigidity, as you said, but also density and shape. The higher density ones - that has the core, and therefore also have the rigidity - perform better because they have more motion energy; they pack a heavier punch. But also the shape, I believe, the less "flimsy" the shape is, the better it is to deflect incoming blows and to cut. The triangle one is too flimsy, it's more like a folded flat in some ways, too susceptible to incoming blows and cant handle the stress, but round ones are better at absorbing the blows because it can take the punch from any angle and hold up equally good - a blow from the wrong angle tears the weirder shapes faster.

The reason, I believe, the round core and sharp square got to the point they did, was because of those factors. The round core held up great, and technically tore off small pieces first, from what I could see, however, the sharp square cut off larger, and that I believe is due to its shape. While still pretty compact - and not having that many angles that could be torn worse than other angles, such as the triangle - it also had something the round core didnt; it had the small edges. It wasnt like a very fine edge that could easily chip, like a katana (sorry for the nerdy comparison), but more like a non-honed ax. While not very sharp, it was still something that the round core didnt have. The edges, albeit blunt, on the sharp square cut into the outer layer of the round core and weakened it by cutting into the plastic, meaning in the end it was just the core holding up. And the core couldnt handle the centrifugal forces that occured when the two strips met and clashed, it needed the plastic "shell" to do that. It's like rebar inforced concrete, the core/rebar and the shell/concrete handles different kinds of stresses, and if one breaks, the other cant compensate for it, atleast not easily.


The sharp square had that going for it; while still being fairly compact - with no flimsy weird shapes that could get struck at "the wrong angle" and break easily - it had about the same density/weight as the round core, but with it's blunt edges it could do more cutting into the shell of the round core and weaken the round cores adaptability between rebar/concrete, thus in the end break it in larger chunks.

That's what I believe, anyway.

@15:30 it looks like you pinpoint the "wrapping" failure mechanism you were seeing.

1) impact: then the more compliant line wraps around the stiffer line/object

2) perimeter failure: as the compliant line bends, it creates a stress concentration at the outer perimeter of the line at the tight radius, pushing the outer fibers past the ultimate tensile strength.

3) momentum increases: during "unwrapping" the end of the compromised line gains angular momentum, increasing tensile force on the line at the weakened point

4) tensile failure: the axial force created in the line at the moment the unwrapping completes causes tensile failure (perhaps there's also a bit of a shock/fracture type load too).

What intrigued me about your video was that the professional weed eater lines (the crossfire, stihl green line, and the husky titanium force) all had more “noodleing” my hypothesis is that the professional lines have to have more flex because you want durability around hard objects eg: trees and houses. It’s all about economics on these things and the more line you save the more money in your pocket. The downfall of the stiffened core lines is that they do not achieve a cleaner cut that is expected when maintaining properties as a professional. They are used in brush cutting applications. I also noticed that when the crossfire line broke, it was a tear at the base of the head. That was more of a head problem than a line problem. There are many different professional products that combat line tear at base like the echo speed feed 400 heads. It would be really cool if you could continue the lawn equipment series and maybe get it touch with the guys at scag mowers or walker mowers and do a video on the incredible engineering of a commercial mower deck.
